annotation: Sicilian defence

I guess I thought being aggressive would mean I dictate the game. Being white I wanted to use that tempo advantage to stop you running rings around me. It didn't work! From now on I'll save this aggressive style for lower rated players I think.
After the exchange on d4 I feel I am in quite a good position here. Nice centre control and both bishops free to move whereas one of yours is blocked in.
Preparing to castle early.
Looking back this move makes no sense to me. I suppose I was just thinking lets get all the minor pieces developed.

Good  move from you pinning the knight down and threatening the bishop. I think maybe you were hoping for the upcoming exchange on f6 giving you the bishop pair. Since this game I've found out that in grandmaster play trading a bishop for a knight isn't seen as a good move. Here though I'm sure I thought that the bishop and knight were worth exactly the same.
Well at least you have the doubled up pawns here. I never got the chance to take advantage though!
Finally I castle. My king is quite safe (for now).
Forcing me to do something about the double threat to my knight on d4 as well as my bishop on c4.
The exchange is all I saw here. It benefits you though as with the knight on d4 gone your queen is looking quite menacing to my f2 pawn and the king it's defending.
Trying to keep the bishop where it is to maintain at least some centre ground. But maybe retreating the bishop to d3 or e2 would have been better.
Starting an attack down the kingside which would eventually be my downfall.

This move is awful from me. Instead of moving the knight towards the kingside to help out against your upcoming onslaught i decide to put it on the rim of the board on the queenside! My thinking must have been just to get your queen away from the centre but this is really a poor move the knight is now useless for the rest of the game.

I'm preoccupied with trying to force a retreat from your queen. I guess I was thinking pawn to b4 after moving the knight on a4 out of the way but this is a lot of effort to go to just to get your queen back a couple of squares.
The queenside attack continues.....

I try to prevent your pawn advancing any further down the board. But this move has weakened my king safety. In fact even a bishop sacrifice from you here (Bxh3) may not be the worst idea because it leaves my king wide open to attack.
Decided to bring my queen into the game
I think I should have accepted to exchange of queens here. Would mean you wouldn't be able to castle.
Yeah here's the other reason why I should have done the exchange first. Now the king is mightily exposed.
I'm noticing the danger of the kingside now but too little too late that knight should never have been on a4 to start with.
Only one thing I can do here to save material
Good game. Short game but good game!

Decided to annotate this game because at the time my opponents rating was nearly 1400 and mine was around 1250 I felt I played well to win this one.
Wasn't expecting him to do this I have to double up the pawns but I'm ahead in development.
Again 5 moves in and he only has 1 piece out on the board however I felt it would have been more surprising to do this.
Creating a bit of a pawn formation and protecting my knight
Don't know why I done this perhaps I was thinking ahead to an open file when his lsb was out.
Happy to exchange feel I'm in a better position at the moment.
Not to bothered with moving my king out at this point plus if I had moved to the 1st row I would have lost my h1 rook.
Don't know why I didn't take the knight.
Again should have taken the knight.
Bit of a pawn push towards the king
Going to take up his offer this time!
Yummy free pawn!
Another freebie.
This is the move that made my opponent resign
BOOM! A few mistakes from myself but all in all I don't think I done to badly.

The winawer variation. Bobby fischer thought it to unsound but  in the majority of his games he lost.
Black parts with his dark squared bishop to disrupt whites pawn position.The risk is that blacks dark squares may become very weak.
If black can wear out the storm he may be better in a endgame.
main line.
Not the mainline usual here is 6...Ne7 but i wanted to play this old move of Botvinnik which is just as good as Ne7
the main idea black defends the g7 square.
Developing and the same time attacking d4.
The first mistake by white.The knight is headed for f4 but blocks the bishop.
white doesnt grab the pawn because 11.Qxg7 Rg8 12.Qxh7 Nxd4 13.Nxd4 Qc3 check dropping the rook.
I dont understand this move.Blacks position is very solid.
White is not developed but this only leads to a draw with correct play.
Now white is losing .He avoids perpetual check thinking he has a won position but.
not the best defense but 18.Nxf4 Nf5 attack the queen and threatens Nxd4 but 18.Qh3 f3!! wins.
its over
game over black resigns it all over.
The white knight at e4 is undefended.  In addition black's black bishop now has a potential bead on the white rook.
Knight for knight plus pawn.
White defends against Pc5.  Moving the knight would cost a rook and white can't launch much of a counterattack at the moment.
The pawn at g2 is history.
...or not.  Mate is so obvious and easy to defend against I would have gone for the pawn.
White thinks black's rook is better off on b8.
With this move white could pick off the pawn at c7 with his rook (or the black knight) unless black moves the queen.
I don't see black's advantage here other than that the queen is not threatened there.
This trade nets white the pawn at c6 or g6.
c6
Out of the frying pan into the friar.  Or white's black bishop...
The obvious response here is to double tag black's bishop.

Hi everyone!

After a run of bad losses it is nice to talk about a win especially one which involves Glenda The Defender in the position of her dreams!  Well they certainly came true in this one.  Watch this space.  Gameknot Analysis is provided for this game (which starts off as a Sicilian Naijdorf) as follows:- http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=16118151&fb=1&rnd=0.03013906409039291
5. ..... a6 - this little move is the Sicilian Naijdorf.  Moves 1-5 are pretty standard Sicilian moves.  A b5 pawn push/queenside pawn storm invariably follows from this.
8. ..... Be6 - development and black may want to take the knight giving me isolanis at the right moment.
10. 0-0-0 - you would never believe that over the next few moves black's king which looks safely tucked away is gonna be subject to a massive line-opening pawn storm.
11. g4 - are you all sitting comfortably?  Now it all begins!
12. ..... b4 - black gets one going as well but I just happen to be a few jumps ahead.
14. f4 - after both knights retreat the kingside pawn storm begins anew.
16. cxb3 - the B for N trade is forced.  Henry is opened up on the c column but thankfully this does not prove to be a problem.
18. Kb1 - Henry sorts it by moving to b1 out of the threatened discovery Nxe4+.
19. f6 - here comes a line opening pawn sac of which black accepts.
21. Nh5 - bringing a piece into the vicinity of the BK and attacking black's dsb on f6.
22. Qg2+ - as you can see a second white pawn has dropped but that one was very toxic indeed.  Here comes Glenda!
23. Qxe4 - Glenda turns that annoying steed into dust and I am now a N for 2 pawns up.
25. Nxg7 - my knight knocks out the defensive bishop on the g column.
26. Qf6 - Glenda moves in to threaten a nasty discovery (Ne8+).
27. Ne8+ - of which I carry out.

28. Bb5 - the bishop is en prise on this square but I am not too fussed.  Fou Leblanc defends the knight on e8 but more importantly the Wicked Witch of the West is perfectly in line for a pin on the g column.  If the Witch now moves off the diagonal then black can cop Old Matey at Her Majesty's Pleasure!
29. Rhg1 - pin.
31. Bh6 - no need for the rook to eat the Witch yet.  Might as well get a piece in to ensure that black really does cop Old Matey.
32. Rxg6+ - now the rook eats the Witch.  If you have ever played Battle Chess you will see that when the rook captures the queen - he eats her alive!

33. Qg7 MATE!! - yup there it is Glenda in all her splendour is doing what she always wanted to do give the enemy king that kiss of death aaah.  Now there is another player a certain Master that Glenda would just lurve to do this to - I will leave you to guess who!
My favorite opening...
Supporting Knight. My opponent started to get off his Queen earlier... I knew he is aiming Qxf7# checkmate.
Supporting Knight strongly....
My opponent positioning all his pieces to start attack. I knew anytime he started to enter my premises through some pieces...
Now i release my Queen to play herself...
Restriction to enter..
I'll enter your premises first through my Bishop.
Strengthening pawns to attack.
Here you can see closing the room of King with all his pieces to restrict my opponents further moves...
Forced to move my Bishop to open a way for King...
But i didn't bother. Because i have some other plan to catch my opponent's valuable Queen. Just find it out...
My opponent is very happy to have my bishop.. Now its my turn...
hahaa.... Opponent's Queen is locked. Nowhere to go...
My opponent plans to release or exchange Queens followed by check. But i won't give him a gap.
Still his Queen locked.
Give a way to his King....
He lost his Queen...
Now my Queen enters.........
Knight protected.
Gaining pawns...
He doesn't wanna lose more pawns.. Protected by his King.
Planned to give a check at Qc5+.
Trying to threaten me...
Ignored my pawn.. No way to give chance for check... hmm
attacking his Bishop..
Runaway..
Closing the way. Not again..
But my opponent has other plan. Nice move... appreciated.
OK Bishop go away.....
Giving a way to ROOK enter through Rxe5...
i have ignored having another plan.
here i saw his plan to get his pawn passing supported with Knight.
MY VERY WORST MOVE... EVEN NOT THINKING ABOUT THE PAWN.
Here my opponent making a big mistake not taking my rook hanging around the pawn sitting in c4. I don't know why he is ignored.....
I know its the right time to not waste any single move.... planning to give him a check with my knight...
attack from his rook...
WHAT will be the next move of mine...??
Here i'm sacrificing my queen... to have his rook at the right moment. And have my passed pawn to gain again my QUEEN.
GOTCHA... Go my pawn... bring my QUEEN back...
Its very late my dear opponent..... to catch my rook....
Giving my ROOK for an exchange... at the same moment gaining my QUEEN back...
But he ignored....
Gaining his rook. at the same time check...
Welcome my QUEEN...
Have my king to sit in the corner to take some rest.. My QUEEN will see the rest....
One step remaining for my opponents pawn to gain his QUEEN back... Now i shouldn't waste my move.
FORCED...
FORCED AGAIN...
Finally checkmate...  i never thought i can win this game when i make worst move at 30. Rd6. I can't win if i loose a single move...
Another open challenge this is one example of how important a bishop on a nice diagonal can be.
Queen's gambit one of my preferred openings as white
Accepted in my games playing this I haven't seen it accepted that often.
I'm not keen on this response from black though I think it's still within book I don't like that it restricts the knight
This is a bit more passive than my usual Nc3 or e4 but I don't think its bad
Again I am not keen on this move as it renders blacks lsb pretty useless.
This move took us out of the Gameknot database. I wanted to break up the black pawn structure a little and give my dsb access to b2 and a3 as black was now going to have to castle king side.
This move from black pretty much forces me to make a move I wanted to make anyway i.e. Bb2

This bishop stays on this lovely diagonal for the rest of the game. Note that although the diagonal is blocked by a couple of pawns there are no black pawns to stop my pawn on d4 advancing and opening the diagonal further. This proves significant later in the game as we will see.
regains the gambitted pawn and gives my lsb a little more room to maneouvre
As well as shifting the bishop my queen now has an eye on the a2-g1 diagonal

Doesn't really defend the bishop as I have the option of c5 though I am not going to take that option. I'd like to keep my pawn on c4 but won't complain if bxc4 as then Bxc4 leaves my queen and bishop lined up with where I am expecting the black king to soon be i.e. on g8 after castling
Preparing to castle but also commanding the diagonal b1-h7 again attacking the area around where the black king will be after he castles.
All according to plan. note that the black dsb is now out of place and doesn't really have any good options. In addition the black lsb can only move to b7
This was to encourage black to create weaknesses in his pawns around his king
and he obliges.
I think I would have taken with the knight here however I think black is planning c5 opening the diagonal for his lsb
However I now have a plan to attack the black queen with my dsb as we will see.
I think this is a poor move from black to me Bxd5 looks much stronger. With that pawn where it is blacks lsb is obstructed
Threatening the queen. I didn't want to take the d5 pawn as then I would have made life easier for black.
Declines the exchange later on this may prove blacks undoing.
grabbing the open c file
Moving the queen to the nice open 4th rank. As both my bishops and my knight are threatening the area around the black king I can easily bring my queen into the action too.
I was expecting something like Bb7 here leading to an exchange of bishops. I think black was rightly worried about Bxf6
I was very pleased with this move blacks options are limited and I am threatening Nxg7 with some nice threats to follow
Possibly the best response though my dsb still has control over the a1 - h8 diagonal
An unfortunate oversight from black. I was expecting f6
Thanks for reading please comment
Standard Queen's pawn opening.
Fianchetto bishop and castle Kingside.
I decided I wanted to try out a fianchetto on the Queenside also in order to have two snipers for the middle.

In this position I envisioned the Queen on c6 with a clear line to g2 for checkmate.  I knew that in order to have a chance I needed a piece guarding the f3 square in case the bishop or pawn moved into it to stop the mate.  I want my Knight on d5 for this very purpose but the pawn on d4 is a thorn in my side so...
Offering the Bishop to move the bothersome d4 pawn.
Accepted the sacrifice.
Threatening the Knight but I actually want the square it occupies.
Defending the Knight but also moving away from defense of the f3 square.

Continuing with my plan.  I calculated White would move the Knight and reveal an attack on my Queen.  I planned to either move my Queen to e6 at that point to continue toward c6 or take his bishop with my Rook if he moved to g5.  Instead...

I honestly didn't see this spot for the Knight most likely ignoring it (incorrectly) due to pawn protection of d6.  Of course with the Queen under fire taking the Knight does nothing.  I could move to e6 as I originally planned but my key bishop is now under attack!  This foils my original plan and I must come up with a new one.  My Queen Knight and Bishop are all putting pressure on his Kingside...
I am willing to sacrifice another Bishop for a devastating Knight fork...
And he accepts.

Nf3!! And here we see a Knight in Paris.  The g2 pawn is pinned by the black Queen and the white Queen will fall.  White resigns.  Continuation: 20. Kh1 Nxd2  21. Nxd8 Nb3  22. Rb1 Rxd8. And black has won material and retains the Queen.
My favorite.
Interesting enough I have to play carefully.
A loss of time but I want to provide a square for my bishop on h2.
c5 would have been better but not crushing... yet.
I assumed he won't play Bb4 now but without his Be7 I wouldn't have played c4 leaving him Bb4. I'm not sure it would have been good for him even now.
I expected here b6 etc but...
Now I have a very good move. I had it the move before but now it is better because black is closed on the queenside except for... let's see...
Attacking e6. Now it is funny to see that the only way for black to defend is Nb8. Nobody wants to play it so he tries a costly adventure.
I will suffer from the exchange but he has to save his queen first.
Qe8 and it is a plain exchange down. Better to attack. He's right.
I started a queen chase. NxN is not possible.

The queen is already unconfortable here. Note that retreat was not possible. But under normal conditions the queen is not trapped: it threats b2 and the knight is pinned. NxN if I leave him will exchange it and he will save the rook. But...
A poisoned pawn. Qc3 maybe was better since it doesn't unpin the knight (the key). If Rc1 Qxa3 and otherwise I must offer a queen's exchange giving him tempo to save the rook.
Ok the rook is mine.
Very good he takes my castling and cramps me.
I still cannot play Rc1 but now I am not worried: a queen's exchange is in my favour so Qc1 will work. If Qd3+ Ke1 and... what? Black has no other pieces to support his attack.
A deadly overlook.

Really really unusual. The king helps trapping a queen! No way to save it. QxB RxQ KxN leaves white with overwhelming material advantage. I cannot blame him for not seeing this. All started with Nd7 that left e6 unprotected.
Yikes. This just invites trouble.
Obviously threatening 5. Nd5.
Pretty much the only move.
6. 0-0 was possible too.
Mixing things up. If 7... axb5 8. dxb5 Black's Queen must move away from the defense of c7.
This may be "book" or not but I found it on my own. Now Black loses c7.
If 8... Qe6? Nxc7+ wins the Queen. This was his only move incidentally eyeballing White's g2 and e4 although to take either would be to invite more trouble.
Here 9... Kd8 was better I think.
I thought about Bd3 but Black gains time that way with 10... dxc3 11. e5?! Qxb2 12. Rf1 and Black has survived.
This is probably the right recapture reserving the possibility of ...d6 blocking off the Bishop's protection of the Knight at c7. Black also now has the b-file for his QR.
Here 11... Qxe4 was not possible because of 12. Re1! Qxf4 13. Re8=.
The previous note applies here too. Now White must think about how to defend the Knight at c7.

This handles it for now. If 13... Rxc7 14. Nxc5. Now Black should try 13... Bg4 14. Qd3! (not 14. Qd2 Bf6!++) Nh6 15. h3. White still has the edge since the Bishop has no good retreat and the other Bishop can't move from c5 without giving the d-pawn.
Hoping perhaps for 14. Re1 Bxf2+ 15. Kxf2 Qxf4+ 16. Kg1 Rxc7 winning.
Same story with the mate threat at e8. The White Queen is taboo.
Good move except for the tiny detail that White can capture with check gaining a move and saving his pieces that appear en prise.
Entering an endgame two pawns ahead.
Good enough to force a Rook exchange.
But first...more pieces in play!
Just a nudge before taking the a-pawn.
Forcing more exchanges now that the pawn majority is overwhelming.
I might have held onto my 4-pawn edge but Black's Rook will not really pose a danger at h2. Still 32. f4 might have been better here.
If 34. Rxg4 Rh1+ 35. Kf2 Rb1 and White must defend his Q-side pawns.
If instead 34... Rh4 35. Nd3 Nf6 36. Rf4 Kg7 37. g3 Rh6 38. Ne5+.
This allows the exchange of the remaining pieces giving White an unstoppable pawn storm.

When black takes the bishop white's knight is lost.  White could stave off impending doom by advancing the pawn to b4.  Better yet just move Na5-c4.  Black can't press a pawn against any piece in the c file.  Best though is NxPc6.  It's a free pawn as NxNc6 would be followed by RxNc6.
Black's queen bouncing back and forth allows white's pawns to advance free of charge.
This exchange doesn't work out so well for white especially when black had already proposed queen swapping several times.
The bishop feints seem a bit pointless as though black is trying to force white into a position white would prefer.

From a post game discussion white conceived of a plan to capture the black queen with this move.  Personally I couldn't see it.  There is far too much material for white to clear out of the way to pull off any such long range plan.
Black again pushes white to a more favorable position though in this case I understand the desire to promote the a file pawn.
Part of white's plan involves a knight sacrifice.  Seems foolhardy when white is already down four points.
Down seven!  Though really the exchange makes the difference six.
Now black is two moves from a pawn/rook exchange for another four point (-10) material advantage.
White actually makes an excellent move here.  Qh4 would leave the e pawn undefended against the black knight.
Declining the pawn was wise.  Neither I nor white saw the resulting force mate.  White was still inconceivably (to me) eying the black queen.

Black may be defending against the potential threat of white's lined up rooks.  Except why?  Black can take Rd8+ with NxR.  Rd1xN would be followed by Ra1xR.  Barring all that black can still interpose Bf8.  The real threat is Qh7+.  Maybe black was making space for Ne7 or so that the queen could also protect Pg7?
Now here I was thinking PxP then somehow promoting g6.  White however was focused on the black queen.
Oh right!  That white rook is there.

Hi everyone!

Here I am still yet to achieve my first ever Expert Victory in a non-timed out game.  Now wouldn't it have been lurvely to have just done it against The Coach!  Off the board Ion has given me tremendous ongoing support but alas on the board Ion is painfully aware of my strengths and weaknesses and knows just how to tempt me into his tactical traps.  In this game it was not a case of simply walking into a one-move tactical shot and coming off worse I won a pawn in a speculative gambit that Ion played against me and tried to hold on to it at a cost of my development.  This allowed Ion to put a lot of pressure on me in particular the d column and he had a very strong knight which he used to devastating effect as first one black pawn then another dropped.  Gameknot analysis is provided here  http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15730439&fb=1&rnd=0.7837962235268192 to help you follow this game of which incidentally is my longest game against Ion.  He starts off with 1. Nf3 which is called the Reti Opening.

1. ..... f5 of which I decided to try and surprise Ion with a move which could transpose the game into the Dutch Defense.  I remember playing the Dutch against Ion before and losing eventually so I thought that maybe I could learn from past mistakes and do a better job this time round.  However Ion has other ideas with .....
2. e4 .... a gambit.

3. Ng5 as Alice in Wonderland would say curioser and curioser Ion moves the same piece twice in the opening to attack my advanced e pawn after I accepted the gambit.  I decided to play d5.  Although this does not develop a piece at least it opens up the c8-h3 diagonal for Fou Leblanc.

4. ..... Nf6 - maybe I should have undoubled those e pawns at once and played PxP but that would have allowed the Wicked Witch of the West to come into h5 and with a knight on g5 it would have looked really nasty for Henry.  So Nf6 prevents this check.
5. .... h6 - before recapturing I decided to drive back Ion's knight.

7. ...... Kxd8 - hmm I think Henry always breathes a little easier when the Wicked Witch of the West is off the board especially when she belongs to my Expert or Master opponent!  Now I am a pawn up and queens are off the board can I make this count?!
8. ..... Be6 - at least I can prevent a nasty threat (Nf7+ forking Henry and rook) with developing a piece.  Trouble is what should I do with Fou Lenoir?
10. ..... Nbd7 - I continue to clear the decks and if my knight on f6 should be exchanged then another knight can come to f6 protecting my e pawn.
11. Bd2 - Ion also decided to clear his decks.  I now launch a combo to get rid of one of my doubletons for Ion's c pawn.  Alas this decision will back fire on me big time later on.

12. Nxf8 - but first Ion kindly solves the problem of what to do with Fou Lenoir for me.  He voluntarily trades in his active knight for my totally inactive bishop and helps me clear the back decks!  But as I said before on the board when Coach Ion falls in with my plans he has far greater plans of his own!

13. ..... c6 - I do however play c6 before launching that combo first.  This is a multi- purpose pawn move.  It frees up c7 for Henry so that I can castle queenside by hand and it stops Ion from posting a knight on d5 or b5.
16. ..... Bxc2 - that little pawn trade has taken place but I now wonder whether I should have played either Rd8 or Re8 first.  You the Inquest Jury decide!
18. ..... b6 - to create another flight square for Henry b7 but alas it does weaken c6.
19. ..... Rae8 - at last the queenside castling by hand has been accomplished but will it do any good?
22. Bf5 - Ion will not relinquish that powerful bishop pair without exacting a heavy price from Yours Truly.
23. Bd3 - my e pawn advances to close off one diagonal but alas that white lsb finds another.  Henry goes to b7 to prevent 24. Ba6+.
26. Bc4 - this move puts pressure on e6 and Ion's dsb on d6 is three things it's a menace it's a menace it's a menace!

26. ... Nd5 - I try and improve the position of my pieces by easing the pressure on e6 (temporarily alas!) and posting my knight to a more active square.  Now if BxN or NxN then I will recapture with my e pawn and be a pawn up with a solid queenside majority of 4 against 2.  Ion wisely declines this exchange.

28. f3! - if I now play NxN then PxN forces my d5 knight to move and back goes the pressure on my vulnerable e6 pawn.  Maybe that could have been the better strategy though compared with what was to follow.
29. .... Re7?? - this move proved to be my undoing.  It is really awesome and frightening just to see how Ion punished me over the next few moves.

33. Rxd5 - firstly Ion regains his pawn by taking the pawn on d5 taking advantage of the pin on the e6 pawn.  I wonder whether taking the rook would have been the better alternative to advancing the e pawn but I wanted to keep the kingside pawns as together as possible.
36. Rb5 - nasty!
37. Nc4 - and double nasty!

41. ..... Rg8 - my position looks just like Sheffield did in the 1984 Nuclear War film Threads.  A scene of utter devastation.  Although this counter-attack proved to be token I just felt the need to do something to show Ion that I am not simply a certain product of my former company Initial Textile Services Cambridge Division (that small Cambridge outlet used to provide mats to various companies in the Cambridgeshire Suffolk and Hertfordshire areas before it closed sometime in 2008) before deciding to wave the white flag.
42. ...... Rd2 - 4 pawns to the bad I throw everything at Ion's king.  Alas thanks to Ion's pesky knight Ion has another little combo up his sleeve to force a rook trade.
46. ...... Bf1 - after the customary rook trade I throw one last thing at Ion's king Fou Leblanc.
48. ..... Ra2 - all my rook can do is to hold up the g pawn for a few more moves.

50. Nf4 - I now realise this cannot be done and Ion is sure to crown one of those kingside pawns and snap up my h6 pawn.  I now finally waved the white flag.  Ion did say in his post-match pm "I was expecting you to play on for quite a while actually. Yes I had a winning game but you were still in a position to throw a few caltrops in the way of my gallop to victory!   And I anticipated you would play 49...Rb4 but it never occurred to me to play 50.Kg1 in response. I was planning on 50.Kg3 Rxa4 51.Rxh6 then back to the g-file and shove the h-pawn. But 50.Kg1 does have its merits: the bishop has just one square available (c4) so I can see why you would exchange down into the rook and pawn ending. The problem there is that the lone rook hasn't a prayer against R and 3 and even if I had only two or even one pawn the fact that I could cut your king off on the Q-side would have given me the win. So after 50.Kg1 Bc4 would have to be tried." I think 
that I could have played on but frankly I had had enough.  So yet again any thoughts of my first ever Expert Victory remain only in my dreams.  Well played Ion.

Black resigned.

It's my first annotated game and it's only for learning. You maybe have noticed that it isn't a great one but I'd like to learn. Thank you!
So far so standard.
White thrusts forward his Pawns while I focus on piece development.
Securing my King.
Clearing the last minor piece.
I fork two pieces. I was expecting 12 NxP PxN 13 BxQP but White surprised me with a sacrifce to open my King's position up.
After accepting the sacrifice I want to clear space around my King to avoid getting trapped.

Hi everyone!

Another loss in my Masters MT.  I have two games that I need to either win or draw to avoid the dreaded Nul Point.  This was my longest and best game (so far) against Dave Rundle.  I got absolutely trounced in my first two games against him so I am glad to have taken him some distance.  I set out here the Gameknot Analysis version of the game so that you can follow the action:- http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15904877&fb=1&rnd=0.005913757023437383.  Anyhow he starts off with 1.d4 and I decided to reply with the Dutch Defense.
3. Bg2 - this fianchetto occurs a lot in the Reti Opening the English Opening and the Dutch Defense in response to the QP opening.
4. .... Bg7 - of which I fianchetto my own bishop Fou Lenoir.
5. .... 0-0 and Henry is tucked away on the kingside.  Thanks to Fou Lenoir and his steed he does not feel the cold ...... yet.
7. Nc3 - Dave continues to get his pieces out.
9. ..... c6 - exploring the possibility of d5 later on.
13. ..... e5 - but it is the e pawn and not the d pawn that gets pushed to black's fourth rank.
15. ...... f4 - keeping the centre closed but trying to cobble together a pawn storm which does not come off.

18. ..... exf4 - these trades have exposed the WK a little but allowed white a passer on the e column.  Can Glenda exploit this exposure?  Sadly no.  She is just soooo used to defending sigh and double sigh!

21. ..... Kg8 - now Henry really does need a supply of those good old medieval stockings.  The Wicked Witch of the West and Dave's lsb will have some really good diagonals to put Henry under fire namely the a1-h8 diagonal and the a2-g8 diagonal aaargh!
23. Rfe1 - supporting the passer on the e column.
26. .... Ne6 - over the past few moves there have been a couple of trades of one pair of rooks and one pair of minor pieces.  These have proved advantageous to white sigh and double sigh!
28. ..... Kg7 - Henry sidesteps the pin but moves onto a discovery diagonal in line with the Wicked Witch of the West.
29. f3! - this move rules out the possibility of Glenda giving a handy check on g4.
30. ..... Rf7 - the only move to guard the a7 pawn.
32. .... Rf5 - I can see nothing better.
34. e6 - this is very reminiscent of how my game with GM Cyrano ended only I had the white pieces!
34. .... Rg5+ - a spite check.

35. ...... Qb8 - Glenda is threatening Qxb2+ but the Wicked Witch of the West can deal quite easily with that with a check of her own forcing Glenda to capture her and then the Witch will reappear on c8.  As I will be a whole queen down I decided to resign on the grounds of ruinous loss of material.  Here were Dave's comments to this move "...... Qb8 cost you the game! For a long period I was thinking draw but when I played c5 and you played b5 that gave me a chance I would have a look at bxc I also think Rxd6 caused you problems but I could see why you did it so maybe look at alternatives to Rd8 because that move allowed me to put my rook on d6."    Well played Dave!

This move is altogether too defensive.  This position is designed for a fight and White retains all initiative here (as through most of the game).  The Philidor Counter Defense which involves 3...f5 would have been better had Black been determined to move the f-pawn.

Black resigned here (or actually signed off and let the computer resign for him).  Look at the position.  Black is down a rook queen two knights and a two pawns whereas White has given up only the queen a bishop and two pawns.  Black has a vaguely better pawn structure but the isolated d-pawn is going to be difficult to maintain.  White can also castle on both sides whereas Black has just the one option.  Black's white-squared bishop has a limited scope and the same goes for the black-squared bishop.  This game is a disaster for Black and resignation is appropriate.
Here is my 4th OTB game and my first win. There are mistakes from both sides but is worthy of a second look. Please feel free to give feedback.
I like to use Alekhine's defence for e4 openings and tend towards KID or Gruenfeld for d4.
Claiming the uncontested centre.
Entering the Gruenfeld
White chooses the exchange variation. Nf3 is also quite popular.
White now has an impressive looking centre which black will attempt to undermine.
Looking through the centre at the dark squares and preparing to castle. ...c5 is another way to attack the centre.

Reinforcing the White pawn centre and preparing for castling.

...c5 was probably better (certainly more popular) but this seems playable. My idea behind this move was to shift the white bishop off its nice diagonal with ...b5 (if Bb3 then ...a5a6) and gain some space on the queen-side. It provides some more options for the queen too.
I'm not sure why White played this move. It doesn't seem like the most useful diagonal.

I played this with the idea that if White were to exchange pawns there would be 2 isolated pawns to try to defend. if White advances then I gain some free space on the queen-side with ...b5 and load the a8-h1 diagonal with a bishop (this is an option that was already there but I hadn't considered...)

Defending a2.

Not f3. (...Bxf3 could be embarrassing for white!) This move creates a real white square weakness.
Looking to walk around to g2 via h3 or f3.
Nice move by white. Threatening the powerful d5 bishop. Taking advantage of the lack of communication between the black rooks.
Staying on the lethal diagonal and protecting b5 (not that White really has the time to waste taking it!)
White has shored up the holes at h3 and f3. It is a game ending blunder too but I didn't the mate at the time!
22...Qd1+ 23.Rxd1 Rxd1 24.Re1 Rxe1# would have been the correct way to finish but at this point there are too many threats for white to overcome anyway.
Blocking the d file. The stepping stone at h3 is no longer relevant due to the rook at e3.
I thought there was probably a more decisive move but I couldn't find it. ...e4 just blocks the diagonal for the bishop Qh3 doesn't work. this move threatens ...f4 with many threats.
Seems like the best defence.

White resigns and I get to chalk up my first win. Thanks for reading all comments welcome!
I rarely see this opening and I think the last time I remember seeing it was from studying a 19th century game. I'm sure the pawn is bait ...
... but I think I can play this to my advantage so I move out to the center and threaten to take the baited pawn.
I take the bait and ...

... white offers another poisoned pawn. Having studied this opening in a 19th century game I know not to take the second pawn. If I do the white bishop takes b7 and then takes a8 one move later. For the gain of two pawns black loses a pawn and a rook.
I pull the bishop back to protect my own pawn. This move block's the king's pawn and hence makes it harder for my dark square bishop to get out and join the fight.

I guessed white would bring the queen out early to put me in check. Possible responses are to bring back the bishop to d7 and threaten the queen move the knight to c6 to block the queen's attack block with my own queen or use a lowly pawn. Regardless of black's move I suspect white will move the queen to b4 and threaten the unprotected b7 pawn.
I'm not surprised at the queen move. My options are to push the b7 pawn or move the queen to protect it.

White decides to take out black's bishop take control over the center and have a momentary advantage in material. Here I can retake white's bishop with the pawn and be 1 pawn up but that advantage is too momentary since white can go Qb5+ Nd7 Qxd5 followed by either e6 or Nf6.
Surprise #1! I can threaten the bishop and queen in one move.
A logical way for white to regain tempo and avoid losing the bishop when moving the queen.
Now I have two threats on the white queen. A goal for the next few moves is to get my queen onto the main diagonal where I can take out the exposed rook on h1.
White moves pieces to put pressure on the pinned black knight.
Move the bishop out so I can use the other black knight for support.
Not only is my second knight ready to provide support to the first but the king can now castle to safety.
A predictable exchange of knights.
And the king moves to safety thus allowing the pinned knight to move freely.
Black develops a pawn and puts pressure on the white queen.
The rook takes control over the half-open file and puts more pressure on the white queen.

The knight moves towards the tempting c2 square where it can fork the king and rook. Unfortunately there is a queen protecting that spot so I shall have to move the bishop out of the way of my own queen first.
But white obviously doesn't want my knight that close.
Looks like white is planning a kingside attack with the rook and queen.

I move the knight over to kingside. In retrospect I could have left the knight on d5 and sacrificed the bishop with an attack on e3. If white retakes e3 to prevent me from taking the rook on g1 then my queen has an open shot at the white bishop on c1. That would force the white king to move to f2 to protect the rook against another queen attack. I could then have move the rook from d8 to d1 to further threaten the white rook on g1.
White lines up the queen for a mate threat.
So I have to push the pawn forward.
Woohoo! Free pawn!
But the cost of taking the free pawn is the loss of tempo. If I don't move the knight now white will take it for free with the queen. The pinned pawn on g6 offers no support for the knight.
Move the bishop out of the way of my queen.
Very serious mate threat here.
Surprise #2! This is the move I should have done 6 moves sooner - if I saw the bishop sacrifice back then.
King moves to safety.

I must must sacrifice the queen by taking the rook to remove the mate threat. If Qc4+ instead the king would just move to safety again and my own queen would have no recourse for stopping the mate threat.

At this point both sides are "even" in material in that both have the same sum of points of pieces on the board. However I'd say black has two advantages. One advantage is that black has more pieces and therefore more ability to project power. The second advantage is that black has developed more pieces.
Move the knight out so it can go to the g3 square and fork the king and queen.
I guess white saw the fork and also saw the unprotected pawn on b6.
Move rook to protect pawn. In hindsight I could have also move the bishop out to protect it but at the time I was thinking of moving the bishop to g7 so it can attack white's unprotected pawn.
Once again I move a rook to take over an open file and to scare the queen away.
With the queen there I can now do my knight fork like I planned 3 moves ago. I guess white didn't see the knight fork potential back then.

After Surprise #3 white decided to honorably resign. Upon reviewing the game I noticed white moved the queen in 11 out of 29 turns. White's tactics depended on using the queen often and thereby placing the queen in high risk positions. I usually responded to the queen moves by developing rooks minor pieces and pawns. 6 of the white queen moves were in response to threats against her so she was often moving defensively. By move 26 white still had two undeveloped pieces while black's pieces were projecting power over many squares.

Can you find the refutation? In this game I rather speculatively sacrificed the exchange in return for threats to both white's king and queen - on both sides of the board. I couldn't see any defence. Neither could my opponent who surrendered material and lost quickly. Post-match analysis showed the sacrifice to be unsound. Perhaps against a stronger player I would have checked it out better and not played it. Can you find the defence we both missed at the time?
So my opponent opens with the Reti (Nf3) I grab space in the centre.
This was Reti's favourite although King's Indian Reversed set-ups with d3 and/or g3 are common too.
Perhaps d4 is more aggresive but Black can end up with an over-extended centre if he is not careful.
The most common move in this position.
I continue to develop.

and the same goes for Black.

7. Qc2 is more common but this is perfectly playable.
7.... Qd6 is only the 5th most commonly played move in this position but it had a good record.
So white recaptures.
8.... Qa6 is the only move in the World Database on Gameknot.
9. Qb3 is the most commonly played move.
Black attack the pawn d4.

Now on the database there are 3 games with 10. Nc3 and one with Rd1 - which looks the obvious way to defend d4 - Stoer Andreas (2150) vs. Lautner Josef (2126) which Black one. OK before reading on consider what happens if Black just takes the pawn on d4 now. Why can't he take it?

So why can't Black just take the pawn on d4? The point is that after 10... Rxd4 white has 11. Nb5 attacking d4 and c7 and after Rd7 which is the only way to meet both threats White has Ne5 attacking the rook again with advantage.
So now White has to defend it with a pawn.

This is the parting of the ways. There were 3 games on the database with this position Rb8 ended in a Black win in Szymczak Zbign (2355) vs. Staniszewski P (2405) Nb4 led to a white win in Kristiansen Je (2435) vs. Ornstein Axel (2430) as did Na5 in Manor Ilan (2430) vs. Rubinetti Jorg (2445) so obviously I picked the one Black one!

Now in that game play continued b5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. f4 Bb7 16. Qc2 Bxg2 17. Qxg2. After my opponent's move I thought this made b5 all the stronger. If 12....b5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 and if he recaptures I can take his bishop on d2. The Bd2 also takes the d2 square away from the Nc4 so the only other square is 13. Na3 but b4 forking his knights on a3 and c3 seems strong.
So I played it! Stop! Work out the best move for White here.

And he did the only move to avoid losing material immediately. Now he has surrendered his best minor piece the Bg2 which was proudly surveying the entire long white squared diagonal from h1 to a8. Now if the simple recapture Qxc6 White plays Ne5 and his knights on c3 and e5 in fact cover the white squares f3 e4 d5 and c6 and black is only slightly better. So I played an interesting exchange sacrifice which is not actually sound but takes some refuting!
Hitting the queen virtually forcing the reply.
So he takes the rook.
And I take the bishop. The big threat is Bb7 threatening both the queen on b8 by the rook on d8 and a mate on g2. So find the best move for White now?
Yes he has to move his queen off my back rank so he may as well take a pawn.
So I threaten a mate on g2. I am also threatening Ra8 winning the queen. So stop again and find the best move for White.

In the complications this is where my opponent goes wrong. This is the right move but at the wrong moment. Best was 16. f3 Ra8 and then 17. d5. Play may have continued with Nxd5 18. Qd4 Bf6 19. Qg4 Qb6 20. Nd1 Bc6 21. Re1 Bxb2 22. Nxb2 Qxb2 23. Qxc4 Bb5 24. Qd4 Rxa2 25. Rxa2 Qxa2 with a small advantage to White.
So I take it with the knight hoping to move it again and still play the mate.

White desparately wants to exchange queens to prevent the mate. This is another mistake but the position is lost anyway. Better was 17. f3 Nb6 18. Qa5 Rxd2 19. Nd1 Rd3 20. Kg2 Nd7 21. Qe1 Ne5 22. Qe2 Nxf3 23. Rxf3 Qxf3+ 24. Qxf3 Rd2+ 25. Nf2 Bxf3+ 26. Kxf3 Rxb2 but Black would still be winning.
So I remove his defence of his queen and threaten the mate again.
So he thankfully takes the queen.
but before recapturing I throw in a check which means he can't take the knight back.
This is the best square.
Now I retake the queen.

His king continues to march. The Gameknot computer says 20. f3 Rxd2 21. Rf2 Bb5 22. a4 Ba6 23. Re1 c3 24. bxc3 Bc5 25. c4 Bxc4 26. Rb1 h5 27. Rc1 Nxc1 28. Rxd2 Bxe3 29. Rd8+ Kh7 is marginally better White is -6.53 instead of -9.15 but it is a bit academic now.
Because another piece is going.
Gameknot still prefer f3.
I like taking material.

The opening that we played in this game was not particularly noteworthy..
White's line is perhaps cluttered with the two pawns on the c file but otherwise the position is roughly equal.
I was attempting to draw out white's king side pawns to disrupt his inevitable king side castle.
Wisely done
With white's best developed pieces on the king side I calculated that setting up a queen side castle would be the prudent choice.
Bring pressure to bear on the center... a good move.

Be2 is the first mistake white makes. He has all that pressure lined up against that part of the board. A better move would be Bb3 then moving the queen up to the second file and sliding the rook behind it.. Or Bb3... then c4.
At this point I recognized that the best weapon white has is his pawns.. those need to be rolled back.

This is the 2nd important mistake made by white.. the knight protects the e5 pawn.. without it black losses material. Perhaps white was looking to move Nc4.. to re-position the piece so that it could attack my king side.
White starts to play more aggressively and puts into play a good center combination. Despite being down in material white's pieces are better developed.
This looks good.. white forces Rd5 here..

This is a slip up here c4 is a much better move. Ne4 gives black a quick opportunity to trade away the exposed rook and make his line easier to defend. Ne4 temporarily protects blacks knight from his queen.
Offering the exchange and finally freeing up the back rank.

This move I'm not sure about.. I don't see how white garner's any advantage from moving his rook out. White's queen needs to take a more offensive role the only thing it's doing is protecting the knight when there is no piece on the board that can threaten it. I think Qe3 is a better move because it protects the bishop and at least threatens Qa7.

This is the misstep which costs white the game. Ne4 would have been better.. that threatens the queen and white needs to get his knight to the other side of the board.. as it that spot where his attack needs to go. White I suspect thought that he could win back the pawn.. Qxg5.. Rxe5.. forcing the queen to retreat and then equalizing material with Rxe6. What he didn't see however is c3 is exposed and the consequences of a highly mobile queen.
White doesn't want to let go of the choke hold he has on the e6 pawn..
Baiting Rxe8.. which leads to checkmate.
This protects the rook.. but MORE importantly sets up Qf4+
White tries to equalize material without seeing the impending threat.
moving the king to the back rank losses white's queen immediately. .. but the damage has already been done.

White resigns on the next move. 

The compelling question here is how could white have averted this attack? He needs to stop Qf4+.. Perhaps with the king.. although I would argue that all white needed to do was keep the queen on 2nd rank and move from there to attack black's exposed h and g pawns. 

Like to my opponent for the game.. it was a spirited contest.

I've never seen this opening before I'm still experimenting with "finned" bishops. later in the game my LSB becomes my best weapon and ends up winning me the game.
White makes a pawn chain and defends his e pawn. Black strengthens his center.
White trades his DSB for a knight and GKA says black is up by 2/3 of a point.
white attacks the king-side limiting the DSBs movement. GKA says black is up by 1 point.

according to GKA the game's first inaccuracy(black is +1.25). White is completely underdeveloped and his pawn structure is less than perfect. Black is several moves ahead and has solid pawn structure.
White has traded both bishops for knights. White's king is in the open and black's is tucked away.
Several moves later black is still +1.25. The only change is a pawn wall and black has moved hid rook.
White has finally devolved something and the pawn wall has grown a few spaces. black is +0.92
Another inaccuracy by white opening a hole in the wall here will cost him.
First blunder. Here white should have advanced his pawn not waist a tempo avoiding a trade.
Instead of taking the pawn and capitalizing on the blunder Black blunders away his huge positional advantage. (from +5.77 to +1.29)
Black makes a mistake here restricting his mobility.
White makes a mistake allowing Black to gain a tempo.
Black responded correctly to white's mistake but white makes another one. (here black could pick up a pawn putting him at +3.27 through Bg5)
Black makes a MAJOR blunder that could lose him a bishop.
White responds correctly to the blunder.
Black fights a three point deficit but here white makes the mistake of putting his king on the sideline.
Black makes an inaccuracy. (it seemed like it wouldn't hurt to much but GKA says it loses me 1/2 a point)
Rooks are exchanged then white makes a mistake better would have been attacking the bishop.
White makes ANOTHER mistake. Now black is ready to invade and only down 1.14 points.
Black has taken his pawn creating an outside passed pawn. GKA says that this along with with an inaccuracy from white evens the game up.
Black an white both make an inaccuracy (according to GKA).
White makes a mistake and gives black a major positional advantage. (Black is +0.9)
Black increases his positional lead to +1. Following this move white panics and make a mistake followed by two blunders. Black get's excited by the blunders and does on fully capitalize on them.
White moves his knight to help defend instead of activating his king. Black gets ready to promote. (GKA prefers Bf1 as it gains an advantage in fewer moves. but that is just "win more")
Both mistakes just effect the margin of victory.
This last blunder effectively destroys White's game. (black is +12.2 even with a material deficit)

Black exchanges his final peace for a knight and the ability to promote a queen. (Black is +14.6)
You can see what I mean by black's most powerful weapon the LSB trades himself for two knights. This soldier evens the point values and allows the noble black king to vanquish the cowardly white king.
In two or three moves white will lose his last peace and Black will tear down white's half of the wall.

White realizes that he is lost and resigns.

Leontxo says: "! After 15. Nxb5? BxN 16. BxB Nxf3 17. Qe2 Nxg4! black will get the most of the pressure over c2". I say black's position looks promising. Something must be taken as wrong in white's attacking scheme. It looked suspicious the bishop outcome in e2 and the assumption that attacking was just to push the pawns up (against a fiachetto? it is ok only when you are ready to sac in g6 or something like that...)

A direct strike over the king supported by c4 pawn that proves to be very strong. White is already defending. Note that the rook move blocks Nb5 with the intention to try to annoy or exchanging some minor pieces. But white chooses another plan for defending and again it proves to be any good.
Leontxo says: "Game proves this plan to be slow and wrong; it looks much better 18. Bh6 to accellerate white's attack)"
Leontxo says: "Novelty better than the known 19... e5".

White reinforces Nc3 but I wonder if he had something to fear now. Not e5? self-blocking the bishop's diagonal. The problem is that white doesn't have any way to block the Rf8 to enter into the fray. Another idea could have been hxg6 (now that the rook is no longer in f) followed by Bh6 with an eye on the sac Nf5 to open the black king to the rook's action - if time allows it. Leontxo comments this move "?!".
Trying to reach d5 maybe but this is pointless. Leontxo says: "More solid is 21. a3 Ra6 22. Bd4".

Leontxo says: "Be careful! There are very hidden deadly threats.". He refers to a knight or bishop sac in order to exploit the firepower on b2 which in fact happens later. Leontxo says it on the next move but I copy it here in behalf of a better sight: "The deadly trap: 22. hxg6? Nxe4!! 23. fxN Rxa2+!! and mate in two. If: 22. a3? Bxg4! fxB 23. Nxe4 24. Nxe4 Rxa3#". Nice isn't it? Now I would say that after 22. hxg6? Nxe4!! white should try 23. gxf7+ and if Kxf7 24. Qd5+ exchanging queens and releasing some of the pressure. Black can go 23... Kf8 and white 24. Qd5 all the same. But I cannot say if it saves white.
Nevertheless black finds his way to victory with a difficult-to-see sac.
Leontxo says: "!!" :-)
Seeing the following one can suppose white should have not taken the bishop but it is difficult to find another move that shields white against the powerful black battery.
Leontxo says: "if 24. Nxe4? Rxa2+ 25. Kxa2 Qa6#"
This proves Nf4 was a loss of tempo.

This sounds a little slow but white is blocked. Leontxo says: "If 25. Rd1 NxN 26. NxNc3 BxN 27. bxB Qxc3+ 28. Rb2 RxR 29. Qxb2 QxBe3 with decisive advantage". Qb8+ or h6 don't save white since f6 defends everything.

Leontxo says: "? But white had a hidden resource with 25. h6!! whose main idea is that after the previous line white could give mate with Qb8#. The best line seems to be: 25... Nxc3 26. bxN Bxc3+ 27. NxB Qxc3+ 28. Rb2 f6 29. Bf2 Kf7 and the black pawns whort more than the bishop".
It gives white again the mate threat with Qb8+. Leontxo says "Not falling in the trap 26... NxNc3? 27. NxNc3 BxNc3 28. bxBc3 Qxc3+ 29. Rb2 RxRb2? 30. QxRb2 QxBe3 31. Qb8+ and mate."
Renewed attack this time on a2. White has not anymore Qb8+ and no tempo to defend a2 so he must play...

The knight cannot be taken. If 28. NxN BxN and if Nd4 NxR provides black with overwhelming advantage... it is correct? :-) ...and white resigned here. Either if white could have saved it seems that this novelty puts a lot of pressure over white queenside castling putting a question mark over all the scheme of white's attack.
